{"type":"message","id":"c7cc6f32","parentId":"606cefc8","timestamp":"2026-04-12T01:04:20.570Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `iframe` tag is allowed in DOMPurify's ALLOWED_TAGS, but it requires `src` attribute to be allowed. Since `src` is in ALLOWED_ATTR, an attacker could potentially inject an iframe with a `src` pointing to a malicious site. However, this would require the attacker to be able to store content in the blog content field, which would typically require write access to the blog CMS.\n\nBut wait - if a brand's blog content (which they control) is rendered with iframe support, then a malicious brand could potentially use it to embed content on other domains. This is a medium security concern.\n\nLet me now also check the frontend login/register/auth flow and check the frontend services for any issues. Also, let me look at the WooCommerce plugin telemetry endpoint and the public config service.","thinkingSignature":"232d5881e2dd842f581ac2b04de911ecbc7c74cafbbbd3bc18946aff0069d7d1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yadqclk38xmk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"plugin-telemetry\\|woo\\|WOO\" /home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/backend/src/routes/pruebalo.routes.ts"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yadqclk38xmk_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -rn \"process.env\\.\" /home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/frontend/src/ --include=\"*.ts\" --include=\"*.tsx\" | grep -v \"node_modules\" | grep -v \"__tests__\" | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":54799,"output":301,"cacheRead":11939,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67039,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775955849514,"responseId":"062a2289f4e77a31dbb01f03afa67b44"}}
